ratings.question_text: Your level of engagement with the course was:
What is your overall assessment of this course?
The course was well organized to facilitate student learning.
I received clear feedback that improved my learning.
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the level of intellectual challenge of this course was:
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the workload of this course was:

narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: An appreciation for ecology and evolution, and important those principles are to tackle the biggest issues of our era.

The first half of the course, focused on evolutionary biology, required application skills. Once we learned a concept, we would have to apply it to other concepts. The second half of the course, focused on ecology, was more memorization.
Learned the basics of evolutionary biology
I learned quite a bit about evolution.
Just what the title says, Ecology and evolutionary biology insights. Skills of rooting and analyzing phylogenetic trees and more.

Learned a lot about evolutionary biology and ecology. Also learned about science as a process and ever-evolving field - a refreshing take after high-school level evolutionary biology and ecology. A great way to end the bio sequence and the best module of the bio sequence by far!
Learned key principles of ecology and evolutionary biology and how to approach understanding the biodiversity of the world.
I learned the basics of the tree of life and how the tree of life was created. This course also explained the reasons for evolutionary change and how all life originated from one species.
I learned a basic introduction into eco & evo bio, but also skills in reading scientific papers and doing a literature review of these papers
Learned about phylogeny of life, general groups/classifications/relationships of organisms, ecological concepts that shape how organisms interact and how energy flows through an ecosystem.
Evolution/ecology, memorization, new vocabulary associated with the field
I learned about key evolutionary steps in the tree of life as well as how the tree of life was constructed.
I learned about evolution, a lot of phylogeny, and ecology.
I learned a lot about ecology and evolutionary biology, and how their impacts extend into other scientific fields.
I liked it
This was my first introduction to evolutionary biology and it was an enjoyable experience! I learned about many various animal patterns and interactions with the ecosystem.
learned about topics in evolution and ecology through many case studies; a run-through of the tree of life; increase skill to read and understand scientific papers
understanding of the origins and development of life
i learned about evolutionary biology

Bleh. I have random facts about the tree of life in my head, but I feel like other than that it wasn't a particularly interesting course, as someone who is genuinely interested in ecology. 
Also, most of the info felt quite dated--the class was very pro Darwin, mostly had antiquated ideas on sexual selection, and only glossed over climate change, etc.

knowledge: eeb, historical and modern context
insights: the importance of presentation, how to memorize better
evolutionary biology and how organisms are related
Fundamentals of evolutionary biology and ecology
I learned about the history of evolution and ultimately of life.
I learned alot more about phylogenies and the tree of life.
I learned the basics of phylogeny and EEB.
Concepts about evolution and ecology: speciation, natural selection, the origin of life, etc.
Learned a lot about phylogeny and evolution, pretty interesting overall!
Lots of useful knowledge about evolution and patterns. Also good crash course in ecology and tree of life.

It was fascinating to learn about the origin of life and multiple, complex theories surrounding it. It was nice to step away from the details of molecular, cellular, and developmental biology to explore a wider world viewpoint.
I learned the basics of ecology and evolutionary biology and was also able to learn about the tree of life.
Deeper knowledge of evolutionary biology concepts
I learned a lot about evolution
I learned how to understand and read a phylogenetic tree, and learned about the general evolution of life on earth.
I gained a broad overview of ecology and evolutionary biology and its underlying principles.
I learned more about evolutionary biology.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The content was really interesting and relevant. The slides seemed a bit out of focus at times. More focus and direction, especially when studying for the exams, would be appreciated.
One major strength is how well organized the course is.

I don't think that the way the exams are set up is demonstrating the understanding of the students knowledge. It is more of a regurgitation of all of the random facts that were in the lecture. There were very few questions on the exam that were showing how you could apply it to problems.
Heavy memorization; engaging lectures

Strengths: appreciated engaging lecture format and breaks in between
Weaknesses: really heavily weighted exams
Course periods are way too long (one hour 15 minutes) to stay focused. But the instructor did give breaks which was great to re-focus.

Strengths: Professor Near is a great lecturer. Passionate and quick-paced while always checking for understanding. I learned a lot in this class and despite not being overly interested in E&EB) found myself really enjoying the course content. I liked that there were no high-stakes assignments so I could just focus on understanding and enjoying the course material.
Weaknesses: The assignments are fair and not stressful, though I wish that there was more guidance on the second half of the class. I found myself unsure about the final because there are no practice problems or p'sets to intermittently check for understanding. Perhaps a short weekly problem set that checks for understanding could be helpful.

This course was very interesting but the format of testing was quite difficult. The midterm and final are worth the majority of the class grade, yet we were given no exposure to the sort of questions we were going to see on these tests. This resulted in many of us in the class getting bad grades on the midterm (we have not received the grade for the final yet), but I assume the same holds true for the final. I think a practice test would help prevent this.
The course is well designed for learning and was very engaging.

Strengths: Really interesting content! I love living things in general and I find learning about how they're related and their features fascinating. Lots of cool pictures and "news you can use" or just cool facts. Also builds an intuition for how ecosystems work and in general what life is around you.

Weaknesses: I know some of my friends found this course a total turn-off if you are not interested in the above. Personally, I felt that it covered a really broad range of concepts in a very shallow way. I wish we went deeper into the molecular techniques of some of their analysis. It sometimes felt like lectures were all over the place in terms of the types of topics you choose or the types of organisms we chose to focus on. A more consistent style and way of introducing concepts or clades would be great. Also, I wish the sections were a review of class materials instead of overviews of papers that will never be discussed/tested again.

Course is based in memorization. Obvious that Near is very passionate but this course falls short to others in the bio sequence because it just tests memorization rather than any application of topics that would require deeper thinking.

Professor Near is awesome and organizes and teaches the class really well. Main weakness is just that we could use more guidance in understanding the key takeaways about the papers we read in section.

The course was well-organized and Professor Near made lectures very engaging, even though I previously didn't have much interest in evolutionary biology. The course allowed me to better appreciate all the little things that had to happen and come together to create the world we live in now. However, one thing that could be improved is that I wish we were given a practice exam prior to going into exams. The first exam was a bit unexpected to me.
Weakness is you need to know a lot of random information.

Strengths: Professor Near is a wonderful lecturer. It is really clear that he cares a lot about his students and is truly passionate about the class material. The lectures were clear, engaging, and well-organized. The papers chosen for discussion selections were relevant to the class material. Ed discussion boards were extremely helpful to ask questions and get clarification on the class material. PSETs and writing assignments were useful and helped me to understand important concepts. All assignments seemed to be fairly graded. 

Weaknesses: I don't think the exams properly tested our understanding of the class material. Both exams relied on pure memorization and made it feel like I was just mindlessly regurgitating information directly off the lecture slides. Before taking the exams, I felt like I understood the material well and could apply the information properly, but the exams didn't really test that. The exams just checked to see if you could recite things from lecture. The exams are fair and you know what to expect, but I felt more pressure to memorize the words on the slides than to really understand the content. Memorizing phylogenetic trees seemed a bit pointless. The writing assignments were useful, but I felt like it would've helped more to understand the lecture contents if we had PSETs instead.
The material was approachable, however the course was heavily based on memorization, rather than problem solving/critical thinking, like the other intro bio courses.

Strengths: 2 exams rather than one. enrichment. 

Weaknesses: discussion section felt pretty pointless. it would have been a better use of time to review concepts from class rather than scientific papers. I know reading scientific papers is a skill we should have, but unless you went to enrichment, there wasn't much provision for reviewing the concepts from class because we didn't have the weekly quizzes. 

also it was wholly inconsiderate how they handled the whole final exam situation. for reference, the deans told us on Saturday night that exams would be moved online and some professors would make their exams optional. organic chemistry, physics, and other exams were made optional. not this one. not only was it not optional, it wasn't open note. and I know that some students had an unfair advantage because the exam was structured in a way that made it very easy to cheat (we all weren't taking it at the same time and you were able to see all the correct answers after taking the exam, so theoretically you could have sent a friend who was taking the exam later pictures of the questions and answers. also students fully could have had their notes open while taking the exam.) additionally, we were allowed to take the exam anytime between the 21st and the 23rd, even though the 23rd is technically after the due date for all exams. it was really stressful trying to decide whether I should be studying or packing because of the silence that we received from the teaching staff on what would happen about exams. it would have been more considerate if at least they told us when they would make a decision by. the whole situation was handled poorly, and I don't see why the exam couldn't have been optional. 

the slides were so text heavy. it was hard to understand what we needed to know and what we didn't from lectures due to the lack of detailed lecture study guides like we had in bio 103. 

the memorization. it doesn't seem like he'll be changing this course due to how adamant he is that it's sooo important, but it really isn't. memorizing the entire tree of life is pointless. my life before and after this class are the same. I did not gain anything from having to know the tree of life. but I know there's no point in me saying this because he's so set on making everyone learn the tree of life.

ed discussion: deleting people's questions and responding sassily to our comments did not make for an enjoyable learning environment. I should not be worried about censorship when I ask a question on ed.
I thought the course was pretty good
There was a lot of material to go through, but I think Professor Near did a very good job conveying the information. The slides were very informative and was very helpful for studying purposes.

strengths: great organization (in terms of course and Canvas), lectures and slides were very interesting and informative. good professor.
weaknesses: I felt writing assignments were not necessary -- they were a lot of work and did not add much to the course itself.

Professor Near covered a lot of topics, and while it was a lot to remember, I feel that all of it was very relevant and interesting. Im studying evolutionary biology, so this was my favorite of the BIOL sequence, but I feel that it would be very important for premeds too. I disliked that grading did not rotate to different TFs - my TF seemed like a harder grader than some that my friends had, and this is alleviated in other courses by randomizing who grades different assignments.

I think the grading is really nitpicky and I don't think the memorization style is conducive to learning actual skills that can be applied to being a scientist or doctor. Also, I'm sure a lot of people cheated on the final because it was unproctored and premeds have no ethics. I'm interested in research and I think the intro bio sequence is kind of a mess because the focus is on testing and not research, which is more important to me. Everyone gets a 100% on the written projects, which means that people who actually put a lot of time and effort in don't get rewarded. Also, I feel like the exams are less skill-based and more focused on remembering everything the prof said in lecture. That being said, the lectures are very interesting.

Strengths: discussion section. The papers for this class were genuinely interesting and relatively easy to read, and I found section surprisingly helpful in unpacking them. 
Weaknesses: Dr. Near was not the greatest lecturer. His slides were messy and confusing and sometimes had nothing to do with what he said out loud. In addition, the class and exams were mostly based on memorization. I just made Quizlets with 200 words per exam and did fine. This is not learning.

strengths: professor near. this man was 110% the reason why i even bothered to go to lecture. he is extremely engaging and passionate about what he does, and it's almost impossible NOT to listen to him.
weaknesses: the exams were memorization-heavy, but i guess that's how it is with fundamental courses. i can't help but feel like there's a better way of testing knowledge in order to ensure students remember it after the exam, though
most of this course was memorization, perhaps prioritize problem sets more than exams
Lectures were engaging, slides could be more condensed and provide more information

I thought the strengths were the professor's high level of engagement in the material, which made it fun to learn. However, the weaknesses were in the exams which were pure memorization and did not build upon conceptual understanding.

Professor was very engaging and the problem sets at the beginning of the course were very helpful for the exams. The writing assignments during the second half of the course were not interesting or helpful at all.
I think having more teaching fellows would be helpful especially for review sessions but section was a great place to extend our learning.
Professor Near is a great lecturer, super engaging.
Lectures, lecture slides, and discussion sections were all very informative. Homework was reasonable. No weaknesses!
I think this is the best course in the intro bio sequence. Strengths: engaging lectures, well organized, fair and well-spaced assignments and exams.

Professor Near is super passionate about the subject, which is great and really evident during lectures. Problem sets are approachable and exams are pretty reasonable (though they require ample preparation and memorization). Writing assignments and discussion sections seemed a bit off topic and tedious sometimes but were overall not too bad.

Professor Near is an excellent lecturer, and the course contained the perfect blend of p-sets, short essays, and tests; I never felt bored with only type of assignment because our knowledge was assessed in multiple ways.
Interesting and pretty well taught. Not a ton of practice or review sessions.
All in all, I thought it was very well balanced. It placed more of an emphasis on learning than grades, and I was able to truly absorb knowledge while still excelling.

Strengths: Prof Near! Amazing professor

Weaknesses: Sometimes Near goes through the slides very quickly so it is difficult to understand exactly what he wants you to know but go to enrichment!! Dr. Loreng is very helpful.
I liked that we were given breaks midway through each lecture. The lectures were however extremely long.

The readings for section for this course are very interesting and engaging. However, the pure memorization necessary for the midterm and final of this course do not give an accurate assessment of a student's engagement with the course. This course could be improved by changing the test formats from memorization to more of an assessment about an individual's understanding of a concept presented in the lecture.

The lectures were extremely well delivered and very interesting. The PSETS and writing assignment were helpful in consolidating our understanding of the concepts. The exams were fair. One weakness was that some of the papers were either too technical or too broad as to not be that engaging.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, this course provides a necessary understanding and framework to all students interested in biology. It shows that biology isn't only about the human body, we are only a small part of the equation.
Yes
Yes, you need to take it in order to go to higher level biology courses.
Yes.
Yes for pre-med, no for fun.

You probably are taking this for a prereq, but if you are looking for a *real* science credit but you are not a STEM major, I might take BIOL101 and BIOL104 for a full credit. I learned a lot in this class and (despite not being overly interested in E&EB) found myself really enjoying the course content. If you come in with the attitude of wanting to learn more, I think you will enjoy this course. Don't be an annoying pre-med - knowledge doesn't need to have relevance to you being a doctor to be interesting!

Yes, very engaging introduction to ecology and evolutionary biology. Focuses more on breadth than depth compared to the other intro biol courses, and thus makes it easier to identify other classes that might be of interest in e&eb.

I would recommend this course to another student if they are even slightly interested in ecology and evolutionary biology because the course was overall very enjoyable, except when it came to the midterm and final. I feel that an understanding of the history of life on Earth is important for everyone to have.

Absolutely. It is the best of the bio sequence. Not just because some students think it's easier, which it may only be because of more prior familiarity than other topics, but also because it was well taught and ties together some other concepts from the sequence
No
BIOL 104 is very dense. It covers a lot of content in a very short period of time and requires a lot of memorization. I recommend you start flashcards early if you take this class.
Yes! If you are interested in ecology/evolution, learning about the cool adaptations/features of organisms, or are premed/bio major, I would totally recommend.
Most take it because they have to.
Would recommend if you need to take it. Not super interesting to me personally, especially the parts where we just learn phylogenies.
I would recommend this course to another student if they like/are good at memorization. It was very vocab and concept based rather than application based.
If you are interested in the topics or if it is required for your major/pre-health track, yes.

If you are an ecology student or need this for your major, then yes. Its definitely the most approachable class in the bio sequence, but it would be a better use of your time to take something in the EEB department if thats your interest.
No, I would not recommend this course to another student. but I assume you're not taking this because you want to but for a major requirement or pre-med.
Yes, for premed

Yes, I think this course is a great introduction course for the evolutionary biology major. I wish that this course was a full semester, it would give the class more time to dive into the interesting material.
yes, probably one of the best portions of the intro bio sequence. great professor and cool material.
Best course out of the BIOL intro sequence.
Unless you have to take this avoid the intro bio sequence at all costs. Not good for people who actually want to learn about biology, completely destroyed by morally-barren premeds.

No. If they don't have to take it, they shouldn't. I thought one point of the bio sequence was kind of a sales pitch for each bio major. If so, I am definitely not buying whatever Near is selling, even though I was considering EEB before the course.

yes!! i recommend this course even if you aren't a bio or premed major. actually, if you enjoy anthropology or history, this might be the course for you! prof. near taught the course in a manner that reminds me of storytelling - the story of life, perhaps.
only if they are required to take for the premed course
Yes if it is required.
I would recommend this course to another student interested in evolutionary biology. If you are not and looking for a less involved biology course, I would not.
Yes if you are pre med
This is a great introduction to E&EB  would recommend to anyone interested in the major.
Yes, especially if it is a prerequisite, but also it was a very interesting experience learning about the subject matter.
Yes

It's not a gut but is somewhat interesting. Not the worst premed or bio prereq course, but a more focused bio class may be more interesting for someone looking to fill the science distributional requirement!

Definitely! This was my favorite course in the intro bio sequenceperhaps because it's so different from the others. If you're MCDB or pre-med, this might be your only change to explore evolution and ecology. Professor Near is a terrific professor; the lectures are engaging, and since a workload's quite light, this course tends to be interesting rather than stressful.
Yes, the new perspective you gain of life and bio from this class is quite useful
Not unless required for major or graduate school
Of course! Its general knowledge of our origin and I think each of us ought to learn it.

Yes! Honestly Bio 104 is the best part of the bio sequence. Although at times it felt a bit useless to memorize how many species are in monotremes, eutherians, metatherians, another part of me felt that it was nicer that most concepts were more memorization-based, especially compared to Bio 103 Genetics. I just felt that for the first exam, there was so much content tested and we were given such little time. Exam 2 slightly makes up for that because you're given twice the amount of time for a same length exam.
I would definitely recommend this course to another Yale student. It was very interesting and Prof Near did a great job at keeping lectures engaging.
If you dont need to take this class I probably wouldnt recommend it, but its required for most people taking it. Its not that bad.
Yes for students interested in evolution and biological sciences.
Yes, I would recommend this course to anyone who is interested in ecology and evolutionary biology or anyone who needs to fulfill this prereq.
Yes.
